      "summary": "founded in 1971, the Southern Poverty Law Center (SPLC) is a prominent civil rights organization dedicated to <cite id=\"1\">fighting hate and seeking justice</cite> for vulnerable communities through legal advocacy and education. The organization operates at a significant scale, reporting <cite id=\"2\">$169,857,376 in total revenue</cite> for the 2023 fiscal year. SPLC is primarily known for its <cite id=\"3\">Intelligence Project</cite>, which monitors extremist groups, and its <cite id=\"4\">Learning for Justice</cite> program, which provides resources to foster inclusive school environments. Financially, the organization maintains an exceptionally strong position, holding <cite id=\"5\">$749,083,798 in total assets</cite>, which provides a massive cushion for long-term litigation and advocacy efforts. In 2024 alone, SPLC's legal and policy work resulted in <cite id=\"6\">151 discriminatory bills being blocked or amended</cite> and protected <cite id=\"7\">3,200 naturalized citizens from voter purges</cite>. While the organization is highly efficient in its fundraising, spending only <cite id=\"8\">$0.10 to raise every $1</cite>, it faces scrutiny regarding its massive reserves, which currently cover <cite id=\"9\">69.9 months of working capital</cite>.",
